\ms1 The supremacy of the Son
\m 
\v 1 \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w spoken|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w fathers|strong="G3962"\w* \w through|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w many|strong="G2980"\w* parts \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* various \w ways|strong="G4187"\w*, \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w past|strong="G3819"\w*,
\v 2 \w has|strong="G3739"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w end|strong="G2078"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w these|strong="G3956"\w* \w days|strong="G2250"\w* \w spoken|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w us|strong="G4160"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \bd \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*\bd*,\f + \fr 1:2 \ft I take it that ‘Son’ is being used like a proper name (there is no definite article with it). The Son is the ultimate revelation to us of who God is and what He is like.\f* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w appointed|strong="G5087"\w* \w heir|strong="G2818"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w*, \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w made|strong="G4160"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* ages;\f + \fr 1:2 \ft That is what the Text says, although most versions render ‘worlds’, which seems to make better sense, at least at first glance. But let us stop and think a minute—since God is eternal, the concept of ‘time’ may be part and parcel of this Creation, limited to it and perhaps be a defining characteristic, along with space. But ‘ages’ is plural, and how does one distinguish one age from another? Presumably by the events of history—in other words, the Son controls the history of this planet.\f*
\v 3 \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* projection \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w image|strong="G5481"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w* \w essence|strong="G5287"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* sustaining \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* expression \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w*[S]\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Here the pronoun refers to the Son; the previous occurrences refer to the Father. Below, whenever the referent changes I will indicate this by [F] or [S], which will be good until the next change.\f* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w power|strong="G1411"\w*,\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Why do not molecules, with their opposing electrical charges, burst apart? The Creator holds them together—the Son was not only the primary agent in the Creation, He is also the maintainer and redeemer.\f* \w when|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w Himself|strong="G1438"\w*\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Perhaps 6% of the Greek manuscripts omit “by Himself” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* provided \w purification|strong="G2512"\w* \w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w our|strong="G2532"\w*\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Perhaps 3% of the Greek manuscripts omit “our” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f* sins\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Just as the Son paid the price for our salvation “by Himself”, for those who reject or make light of that terrible price He will Himself tread ‘the winepress of the fury of the wrath of God’ (Revelation 19:15). It is not wise to presume upon God's grace.\f* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w sat|strong="G2523"\w* \w down|strong="G2523"\w* \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* highest \w Majesty|strong="G3172"\w*'s \w right|strong="G1188"\w*,\f + \fr 1:3 \ft “He sat down”—evidently He had the right to do this, and no one challenged Him.\f*
\v 4 having \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w so|strong="G5118"\w* \w much|strong="G5118"\w* \w superior|strong="G1313"\w* \w to|strong="G1096"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* angels \w as|strong="G3745"\w* \w He|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G1096"\w* \w inherited|strong="G2816"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w more|strong="G1313"\w* \w excellent|strong="G1313"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w than|strong="G3844"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G1096"\w*.
\s1 He is superior to the angels
\p 
\v 5 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w which|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* angels \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w*[F] \w ever|strong="G4218"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*,
\q1 “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*,
\q2 \w today|strong="G4594"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* begot \w you|strong="G4771"\w*,”\f + \fr 1:5 \ft See Psalm 2:7.\f*
\m \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*,
\q1 “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G5101"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* ‘\w Father|strong="G3962"\w*’ \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*,
\q2 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G5101"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* ‘\w Son|strong="G5207"\w*’ \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*?”\f + \fr 1:5 \ft See 2 Samuel 7:14.\f*
\m 
\v 6 \w Again|strong="G3825"\w*, \w when|strong="G3752"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* introduces \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Firstborn|strong="G4416"\w*\f + \fr 1:6 \ft In Hebrew culture the firstborn son usually inherited the lion's share of the father's estate (so as not to splinter the estate) and was thus the boss, so the expression ‘firstborn’ took on the extended meaning of ‘preeminent’, which I take to be the intended meaning here. But as the God-man Christ was both only-begotten and firstborn.\f* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w inhabited|strong="G3625"\w* \w earth|strong="G3625"\w*\f + \fr 1:6 \ft I assume that this must have happened at the incarnation of the Son.\f* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w says|strong="G3004"\w*,
\q1 “\w Let|strong="G1161"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*'s angels \w worship|strong="G4352"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*[S].”\f + \fr 1:6 \ft See Psalm 97:7.\f*
\m 
\v 7 Further, \w about|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* angels \w He|strong="G2532"\w*[F] \w says|strong="G3004"\w*,
\q1 “\w Who|strong="G3588"\w* \w makes|strong="G4160"\w* \w His|strong="G4160"\w* angels \w winds|strong="G4151"\w*,\f + \fr 1:7 \ft The Greek word here also means ‘spirits’, but ‘winds’ fits the Hebrew parallelism better.\f*
\q2 \w His|strong="G4160"\w* \w servants|strong="G3011"\w* flames \w of|strong="G4151"\w* \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*”;\f + \fr 1:7 \ft See Psalm 104:4.\f*
\m 
\v 8 \w while|strong="G1161"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* says:
\q1 “\w Your|strong="G2532"\w* \w throne|strong="G2362"\w*, O \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w forever|strong="G1519"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w ever|strong="G1519"\w*;\f + \fr 1:8 \ft The author is saying that the Father declares this to the Son. If the Father declares something, that is the way it is.\f*
\q2 ‘\w Scepter|strong="G4464"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* Uprightness’\f + \fr 1:8 \ft I take ‘Scepter of Uprightness’ to be a proper name (like the sword ‘Excalibur’).\f* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w scepter|strong="G4464"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Your|strong="G2532"\w* kingdom.
\q1 
\v 9 \w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* loved \w righteousness|strong="G1343"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w hated|strong="G3404"\w* lawlessness,
\q1 \w therefore|strong="G1223"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w Your|strong="G1223"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w anointed|strong="G5548"\w* \w You|strong="G4771"\w*
\q2 \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w oil|strong="G1637"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* exultation \w beyond|strong="G3844"\w* \w Your|strong="G1223"\w* \w companions|strong="G3588"\w*.”\f + \fr 1:9 \ft See Psalm 45:6-7.\f*
\m 
\v 10 \w Also|strong="G2532"\w*:
\q1 “\w You|strong="G4771"\w*, \sc \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*\sc*,\f + \fr 1:10 \ft The quote is from Psalm 102:25-27, and in that context it is Jehovah who is being addressed, Jehovah the Son. This is one of several passages in the New Testament that contradict the heresy of the ‘Jehovah's Witnesses’ and Mormons that denies that Jesus Christ is Jehovah. From this passage, and a few others, we may understand that the Son was the primary agent in the creation of our planet.\f* \w in|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* beginning, \w laid|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w foundation|strong="G2311"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w earth|strong="G1093"\w*,
\q2 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w heavens|strong="G3772"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w works|strong="G2041"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Your|strong="G2962"\w* \w hands|strong="G5495"\w*;
\q1 
