\m 
\v 14 \w Are|strong="G1510"\w* \w they|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3780"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w ministering|strong="G3010"\w* \w spirits|strong="G4151"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* \w sent|strong="G4151"\w*\f + \fr 1:14 \ft This participle being in the present tense, I take it that this is an ongoing activity. So who will ‘inherit salvation’? True believers, and if we are among them, then we have angels serving us. I submit that we probably have a lot to learn about how to best take advantage of that service.\f* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w serve|strong="G1248"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w going|strong="G3195"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w inherit|strong="G2816"\w* \w salvation|strong="G4991"\w*?
\c 2
\s1 Do not neglect the great salvation
\m 
\v 1 \w So|strong="G3379"\w* \w then|strong="G1223"\w*, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* really \w must|strong="G1163"\w* \w pay|strong="G4337"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* utmost \w attention|strong="G4337"\w* \w to|strong="G1163"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w things|strong="G3778"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* heard, \w so|strong="G3379"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w not|strong="G3379"\w* \w drift|strong="G3901"\w* \w away|strong="G3901"\w*.\f + \fr 2:1 \ft Drifting is gradual, easy to do.\f*
\v 2 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w spoken|strong="G2980"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* angels \w became|strong="G1096"\w* binding, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w violation|strong="G3847"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w disobedience|strong="G3876"\w* \w received|strong="G2983"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* deserved \w penalty|strong="G3405"\w*,\f + \fr 2:2 \ft Verse 2 is reminiscent of the closing charge in Stephen's defense: “You who received the Law as ‘ordinances of angels’ and have not kept it!” (Acts 8:53). I confess that I do not understand where the angels come in to the giving of the Law.\f*
\v 3 \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w shall|strong="G2962"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w escape|strong="G1628"\w* \w if|strong="G3748"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* careless \w about|strong="G1519"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* tremendous \w salvation|strong="G4991"\w*?—\w it|strong="G1223"\w* \w received|strong="G2983"\w* \w its|strong="G5259"\w* beginning \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*'\w s|strong="G2962"\w* declaration \w and|strong="G2962"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* confirmed \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w us|strong="G1519"\w* \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* heard \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*[\w S|strong="G2962"\w*],\f + \fr 2:3 \ft By expressing himself in this way the author lets us know that he was not one of the Twelve.\f*
\v 4 \w God|strong="G2316"\w* adding \w His|strong="G2532"\w*[F] attestation \w by|strong="G2596"\w* \w signs|strong="G4592"\w*, \w wonders|strong="G5059"\w*, \w various|strong="G4164"\w* \w miracles|strong="G1411"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* distributions \w of|strong="G4151"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* own \w will|strong="G2316"\w*.\f + \fr 2:4 \ft Verses 3 and 4 overtly refer to all three persons of the Godhead. For more on the “distributions” see 1 Corinthians 12:11.\f*
\s1 Temporarily lower than the angels
\p 
\v 5 \w Because|strong="G1063"\w* \w it|strong="G1063"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w to|strong="G3195"\w* angels \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w has|strong="G3739"\w* \w subjected|strong="G5293"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G3195"\w* \w inhabited|strong="G3625"\w* \w earth|strong="G3625"\w*,\f + \fr 2:5 \ft The new earth that follows this one will not be administered by angels, so who will do the administering? I agree with those who hold that this life is a classroom wherein the redeemed are being prepared for their functions in the new earth, and some of those functions will be administrative. That future is part of our “tremendous salvation”!\f* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w we|strong="G3739"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w speaking|strong="G2980"\w*;
\v 6 \w rather|strong="G2228"\w*, \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G1510"\w* \w place|strong="G4225"\w* \w where|strong="G4225"\w* \w someone|strong="G5100"\w* \w testified|strong="G1263"\w*\f + \fr 2:6 \ft I find this turn of phrase to be curious; the author knew his Old Testament well, and presumably knew he was citing a Psalm (8:4-6)—why such a roundabout reference?\f* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*:
\q1 “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w man|strong="G5100"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w You|strong="G3754"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w mindful|strong="G3403"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w him|strong="G1980"\w*,
\q2 \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w man|strong="G5100"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G3754"\w* care \w for|strong="G3754"\w* \w him|strong="G1980"\w*?
\q1 
\v 7 \w You|strong="G2532"\w* \w made|strong="G1642"\w* \w him|strong="G2532"\w* \w lower|strong="G1642"\w* \w than|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* angels, \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w little|strong="G1024"\w* \w while|strong="G1024"\w*;\f + \fr 2:7 \ft The human being is superior to the angelic being in essence; we bear God's image and they do not, and once glorified that superiority will be obvious, but only for the redeemed. Those who serve Satan subordinate themselves to him, and thus can never rise above him. If Lucifer's rebellion was provoked, as I suppose, by the creation of a being superior to him, he is doing very well at getting his ‘revenge’, by depriving the vast majority of humanity of that superiority (and so the next verse does not apply to them).\f*
\q2 \w You|strong="G2532"\w* \w crowned|strong="G4737"\w* \w him|strong="G2532"\w* \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w honor|strong="G5092"\w*,\f + \fr 2:7 \ft Some 25% of the Greek manuscripts add, “and set him over the works of your hands”, as in TR, AV, NKJV.\f*
\q1 
\v 8 \w You|strong="G1722"\w* \w subjected|strong="G5293"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w under|strong="G5270"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* \w feet|strong="G4228"\w*.”
\m \w It|strong="G1161"\w* follows \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w subjecting|strong="G5293"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w He|strong="G1161"\w* left \w nothing|strong="G3762"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3762"\w* \w so|strong="G1161"\w* \w subjected|strong="G5293"\w*. \w However|strong="G1161"\w*, \w we|strong="G1063"\w* \w do|strong="G3708"\w* \w not|strong="G3762"\w* \w yet|strong="G1161"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w everything|strong="G3956"\w* \w subjected|strong="G5293"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w present|strong="G3568"\w*.
\p 
\v 9 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w see|strong="G5092"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* ‘\w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w made|strong="G2316"\w* \w lower|strong="G1642"\w* \w than|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* angels, \w for|strong="G5228"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w little|strong="G1024"\w* \w while|strong="G1161"\w*’\f + \fr 2:9 \ft Instead of “lower than the angels, for a little while”, AV, NKJV and some other versions have ‘a little lower than the angels’, both here and in Psalm 8. The Greek adjective here is ambiguous, it can refer either to duration or to quantity (and so for the Hebrew adjective in Psalm 8). In this context the duration is clearly better, or so I deem.\f* (\w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w order|strong="G3704"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w suffer|strong="G2532"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*), ‘\w crowned|strong="G4737"\w* \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w honor|strong="G5092"\w*’—\w this|strong="G3588"\w*, \w by|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w*[S] \w might|strong="G2532"\w* \w taste|strong="G1089"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w* \w on|strong="G5228"\w* \w behalf|strong="G5228"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w everyone|strong="G3956"\w*.\f + \fr 2:9 \ft “Everyone” is not a synonym for ‘the elect’. The death of Christ is adequate, sufficient to provide salvation for all human beings, and is there for them; of course not all actually avail themselves of it (most never even heard about it)—in fact, Sovereign Jesus referred to them as ‘few’ in His day (Matthew 7:14).\f*
\s1 “Bringing many sons into glory”
\p 
\v 10 \w Because|strong="G1223"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* appropriate \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*[F], \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w*, \w in|strong="G1519"\w* bringing \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w sons|strong="G5207"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*,\f + \fr 2:10 \ft This contrasts with the many more who will never see the glory.\f* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w complete|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Author \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w salvation|strong="G4991"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w sufferings|strong="G3804"\w*.\f + \fr 2:10 \ft As it says in 5:8 below, “He learned obedience by the things that He suffered.” As God, what could He know about suffering and obedience, except in theory? While in human form Jesus literally learned obedience. To be a compassionate High Priest He had to feel it like we feel it.\f*
\v 11 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w*[S] \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* sanctifying \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w sanctified|strong="G3956"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w One|strong="G1520"\w*, \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w reason|strong="G1223"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w ashamed|strong="G1870"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w call|strong="G2564"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* ‘brothers’,
\v 12 \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*,
\q1 “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1473"\w* declare \w Your|strong="G1722"\w* \w name|strong="G3686"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w my|strong="G1722"\w* brothers;
\q2 \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w midst|strong="G3319"\w* \w of|strong="G3686"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w congregation|strong="G1577"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G1473"\w* \w sing|strong="G5214"\w* \w praise|strong="G5214"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w You|strong="G4771"\w*.”
\m 
\v 13 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*,
\q1 “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w put|strong="G1325"\w* \w my|strong="G3708"\w* \w trust|strong="G3982"\w* \w in|strong="G1909"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*[F]”;
\m \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*,
\q1 “\w Here|strong="G2400"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w children|strong="G3813"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w given|strong="G1325"\w* \w me|strong="G1325"\w*.”\f + \fr 2:13 \ft See Psalms 22:22, 2 Samuel 22:3, Isaiah 8:17-18—the author knew his Old Testament.\f*
\p 
\v 14 \w Since|strong="G1893"\w*, \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w children|strong="G3813"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* blood \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w share|strong="G2841"\w*, \w He|strong="G2532"\w*[\w S|strong="G2192"\w*] Himself \w likewise|strong="G2532"\w* \w partook|strong="G3348"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w same|strong="G3778"\w*, \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w order|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w His|strong="G1223"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w might|strong="G2532"\w* abolish \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w one|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w*\f + \fr 2:14 \ft “\nd Had\nd*”, not ‘has’ (as in NIV, etc.)—in Revelation 1:18 the glorified Christ affirms that He now holds the ‘keys’. Although the participle of the verb ‘to have’ is in the present tense, that indicates that it is simultaneous with the time of the finite verb to which it is subordinate, which in this case is ‘to partake’, which is in the past tense. Here we have one of a few overt statements giving the purpose of the Incarnation—to abolish Satan. See also Romans 14:9, 2 Corinthians 5:15 and Philippians 2:8-11.\f* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w power|strong="G2904"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*—\w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w devil|strong="G1228"\w*—
\v 15 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w set|strong="G2532"\w* \w free|strong="G3956"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* [\w the|strong="G2532"\w* children] \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w during|strong="G1223"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w whole|strong="G3956"\w* \w lifetime|strong="G2198"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w subject|strong="G1777"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w slavery|strong="G1397"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w fear|strong="G5401"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w*.\f + \fr 2:15 \ft The fear of death is a bad master; it drives people to do incredibly stupid things.\f*
\v 16 (\w Now|strong="G3756"\w* \w surely|strong="G1222"\w* \w He|strong="G1063"\w* does \w not|strong="G3756"\w* assist angels,\f + \fr 2:16 \ft Angels are simply God's servants, so the term ‘assist’ is not appropriate for them.\f* \w but|strong="G1063"\w* \w He|strong="G1063"\w* does assist Abraham's \w seed|strong="G4690"\w*.)
\v 17 \w That|strong="G2443"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w why|strong="G1519"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* obliged \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w like|strong="G2596"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* ‘brothers’ \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w respects|strong="G3956"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w could|strong="G3588"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w merciful|strong="G1655"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w faithful|strong="G4103"\w* \w high|strong="G3956"\w* priest, \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* concerns \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w with|strong="G4314"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w view|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w making|strong="G2532"\w* \w propitiation|strong="G2433"\w*\f + \fr 2:17 \ft ‘Propitiation’ is a theological term; God's righteous character has been outraged by human sin, and something must be done to ‘satisfy’/‘pacify’ that outraged character. Christ's sacrifice propitiated God, satisfied/pacified His outraged character. The resurrection is the proof that the Father accepted the sacrifice, that He declared Himself to be satisfied.\f* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* sins \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w*.
\v 18 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* Himself \w endured|strong="G3958"\w* \w suffering|strong="G3958"\w*, having \w been|strong="G1410"\w* \w tested|strong="G3985"\w*,\f + \fr 2:18 \ft The Greek word here covers both ‘to test’ and ‘to tempt’ (to tempt is to test one's moral fiber), the choice in English being guided by the context. Jesus was not tested only in the area of morals; He was tested physically as well. We too are tested in a variety of ways.\f* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G1410"\w* assist \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w being|strong="G1722"\w* \w tested|strong="G3985"\w*.
\c 3
\s1 The Apostle and High Priest of our confession
\m 
\v 1 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w then|strong="G2532"\w*, holy brothers, \w you|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* share \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w celestial|strong="G2032"\w* \w calling|strong="G2821"\w*, \w do|strong="G2532"\w* contemplate \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Apostle \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w High|strong="G2532"\w* Priest \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w confession|strong="G3671"\w*,\f + \fr 3:1 \ft To ‘confess’ is much more than to ‘profess’, it involves commitment.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* Christ!\f + \fr 3:1 \ft Here we have the first indication as to the addressees; the missive is addressed to Christians. Perhaps 3% of the Greek manuscripts omit “Christ” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*
\v 2 \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w faithful|strong="G4103"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w One|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w appointed|strong="G4160"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w all|strong="G3650"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w*[F] \w house|strong="G3624"\w*.
