\v 6 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w yet|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w fallen|strong="G3895"\w* \w away|strong="G3895"\w*—\w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w would|strong="G2316"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* crucifying \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w all|strong="G2532"\w* \w over|strong="G1519"\w* \w again|strong="G3825"\w*, \w just|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w themselves|strong="G1438"\w*, \w holding|strong="G3856"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* contempt.\f + \fr 6:6 \ft No amount of theological shifting and squirming can nullify the plain meaning of this verse. The only way to crucify Jesus \bd again\bd* is if you have already done so once before. No one is going to kill Jesus twice; if the first time was not good enough for you, you have had it! Anyone who holds Jesus “up to contempt” can expect wrath.\f*
\p 
